00:31:52.160 --> 00:31:52.660
Thank you.

00:31:52.660 --> 00:31:53.550
Go ahead.

00:31:53.550 --> 00:31:57.250
AUDIENCE: Hi, great talk
and I loved the excerpt.

00:31:57.250 --> 00:31:58.750
I just have a really
quick question.

00:31:58.750 --> 00:32:03.030
So I'm now with fiction like
Game of Thrones coming out,

00:32:03.030 --> 00:32:06.380
your novels which are much more
realistic, yours has much more

00:32:06.380 --> 00:32:12.090
moral gray area, if
there's still a place for,

00:32:12.090 --> 00:32:15.280
of if there will be
a place for-- it's

00:32:15.280 --> 00:32:17.890
almost a pejorative
term, but escapism?

00:32:17.890 --> 00:32:19.970
Or novels that
deal with escapism?

00:32:19.970 --> 00:32:24.210
I mean, part of the function
of novels where the heroes are

00:32:24.210 --> 00:32:25.866
good guys and the
bad guys are bad guys

00:32:25.866 --> 00:32:27.740
and the heroes are
honorable, and the bad guy

00:32:27.740 --> 00:32:32.100
are just dastardly and there's
a titanic objects somewhere

00:32:32.100 --> 00:32:35.880
in the distance, all that
kind of good stuff is, you,

00:32:35.880 --> 00:32:38.130
after a long day go
home and read this book

00:32:38.130 --> 00:32:41.240
and it's escapism, and
you don't necessarily

00:32:41.240 --> 00:32:44.220
get all of the stuff you would
be reading Game of Thrones

00:32:44.220 --> 00:32:48.380
or the Magician's
Trilogy, but you get that.

00:32:48.380 --> 00:32:50.660
And I'm wondering if there's
a place for that still?

00:32:50.660 --> 00:32:53.890
Or if that's going away, and if
we should be happy about that

00:32:53.890 --> 00:32:56.371
if it is?

00:32:56.371 --> 00:32:58.370
LEV GROSSMAN: I'm going
to respectfully disagree

00:32:58.370 --> 00:32:59.786
with the premise
of your question.

00:32:59.786 --> 00:33:01.020
AUDIENCE: OK.

00:33:01.020 --> 00:33:07.160
LEV GROSSMAN: I have never felt
that escapism was a real thing.

00:33:07.160 --> 00:33:10.660
To me-- and I say to me,
because literally this

00:33:10.660 --> 00:33:12.800
is my personal opinion--
for at least for me

00:33:12.800 --> 00:33:14.870
it's a fundamental
misunderstanding

00:33:14.870 --> 00:33:20.120
of what reading does for me,
especially reading fantasy.

00:33:20.120 --> 00:33:24.050
You know, I think
it's an easy shot

00:33:24.050 --> 00:33:28.370
to take to say that
fantasy is escapism,

00:33:28.370 --> 00:33:33.680
it is a way of avoiding
the real world.

00:33:33.680 --> 00:33:36.924
This is obviously a
hobby horse of mine.

00:33:36.924 --> 00:33:38.590
Let's go back to the
18th century first.

00:33:41.830 --> 00:33:45.980
You know, at some point
it was the 18th century.

00:33:45.980 --> 00:33:50.220
Sort of, reading culture
developed a huge obsession

00:33:50.220 --> 00:33:51.120
with realism.

00:33:51.120 --> 00:33:54.130
Realism, for some reason,
clamped down on literature

00:33:54.130 --> 00:33:58.730
and became the definition
of what literature was.

00:33:58.730 --> 00:34:01.900
Fictional worlds were supposed
to look like the real world.

00:34:01.900 --> 00:34:05.040
It's like around Robinson
Crusoe or something like that.

00:34:05.040 --> 00:34:09.699
And the other stuff, the fantasy
stuff, you know, the goblins ,

00:34:09.699 --> 00:34:13.010
whatever else, it got pushed
into various different margins.

00:34:13.010 --> 00:34:14.639
It got pushed down
to the children.

00:34:14.639 --> 00:34:17.630
It got pushed off to
the supermarket racks,

00:34:17.630 --> 00:34:21.290
you know, Gothic
literature, to the genres.

00:34:21.290 --> 00:34:24.409
And this, you know,
death-grip of realism, it only

00:34:24.409 --> 00:34:26.790
tightened when the
Modernists came along

00:34:26.790 --> 00:34:29.449
who really codified it.

00:34:29.449 --> 00:34:32.610
But that wasn't always the case.

00:34:32.610 --> 00:34:36.834
You go back a little further,
you get into Shakespeare.

00:34:36.834 --> 00:34:38.000
Shakespeare's not a realist.

00:34:38.000 --> 00:34:45.167
He writes about witches,
ghosts, monsters, magic fairies.

00:34:45.167 --> 00:34:48.850
You know, anywhere back past
1700 and it's all fantasy.

00:34:48.850 --> 00:34:50.409
That's what literature was.

00:34:50.409 --> 00:34:53.100
And we don't think
of that as escapist.

00:34:53.100 --> 00:34:57.760
And what we think
of it is as a way

00:34:57.760 --> 00:35:01.670
of confronting with, or
getting a grip on the problems

00:35:01.670 --> 00:35:06.285
that we deal with in reality in
a kind of transmogrified form.

00:35:06.285 --> 00:35:10.050
You know, it's a way of
getting more direct access

00:35:10.050 --> 00:35:14.700
to the junk that hangs down
underneath your conscious mind.

00:35:14.700 --> 00:35:18.540
You know, you just you all those
subconscious monsters get out

00:35:18.540 --> 00:35:20.622
and they start to look
like real monsters

00:35:20.622 --> 00:35:21.872
and you can wrestle with them.

00:35:24.590 --> 00:35:26.600
That is what fantasy
is about for me.

00:35:30.085 --> 00:35:32.881
It's a way, not of
getting away from reality,

00:35:32.881 --> 00:35:34.630
it's another way of
coming at the problems

00:35:34.630 --> 00:35:36.754
that you deal with in
reality, and getting traction

00:35:36.754 --> 00:35:39.580
on them form a slightly
different angle.

00:35:39.580 --> 00:35:42.190
Somebody, and I forget
who it is, and I'm

00:35:42.190 --> 00:35:48.300
going to mangle the quote,
said a very wise thing to me

00:35:48.300 --> 00:35:54.630
once which was, "fantasy
isn't how we escape reality,

00:35:54.630 --> 00:35:58.020
it's what we need in order
to be able to stay in reality

00:35:58.020 --> 00:35:59.530
and survive in it."

00:35:59.530 --> 00:36:01.100
And I truly believe that.

00:36:01.100 --> 00:36:02.650
I truly believe that.

00:36:02.650 --> 00:36:06.490
And you know, it's partly--
and you do look back

00:36:06.490 --> 00:36:13.680
at Tolkien and Lewis and it is
much clearer, the moral lines.

00:36:13.680 --> 00:36:16.370
You know, which is-- it's an
interesting complicated thing.

00:36:16.370 --> 00:36:19.230
And I can only think that at
that historical moment, that's

00:36:19.230 --> 00:36:20.220
what they needed.

00:36:20.220 --> 00:36:23.080
And our moment is so much
different from theirs,

00:36:23.080 --> 00:36:26.140
and we need something different.

00:36:26.140 --> 00:36:28.170
There you have a personal
theory of mind, which

00:36:28.170 --> 00:36:32.300
has no factual substantiation.

00:36:32.300 --> 00:36:35.710
But it's how I think
about that question.

00:36:35.710 --> 00:36:39.227
And who knows what fantasy is
going to start looking like.

00:36:39.227 --> 00:36:40.810
I don't know, but
it'll look like what

00:36:40.810 --> 00:36:42.910
we need it to look like.

00:36:42.910 --> 00:36:44.750
AUDIENCE: So a lot
of fantasy books

00:36:44.750 --> 00:36:47.524
come in these series that
just sort of go on forever

00:36:47.524 --> 00:36:49.065
and ever and ever
and you can sort of

00:36:49.065 --> 00:36:51.394
continue to follow
Pug and whoever

00:36:51.394 --> 00:36:53.810
your favorite characters through
books and books and books

00:36:53.810 --> 00:36:54.309
and books.

00:36:54.309 --> 00:36:57.200
So how do you feel about that?

00:36:57.200 --> 00:36:59.867
Not with respect other people's,
but with your own world?

00:36:59.867 --> 00:37:01.450
I mean, is this a
world that you would

00:37:01.450 --> 00:37:03.450
want to have inhabit
forever and ever and ever?

00:37:03.450 --> 00:37:06.890
And have Quentin go on and
become an old geezer himself?

00:37:06.890 --> 00:37:10.230
Or is it something that you'd
want to see something new?

00:37:10.230 --> 00:37:13.060
How do you feel about-- what are
your theories about these sorts

00:37:13.060 --> 00:37:14.410
of trade-offs?

00:37:14.410 --> 00:37:16.450
LEV GROSSMAN: Yeah,
well, they're evolving.

00:37:21.427 --> 00:37:22.010
Next question.

00:37:24.830 --> 00:37:28.150
When I wrote, "The Magicians,"
I wrote it as a one-off.

00:37:28.150 --> 00:37:30.790
It actually didn't occur
to me that I would never go

00:37:30.790 --> 00:37:32.310
anywhere else with that story.

00:37:35.100 --> 00:37:38.120
And that was partly because,
when I was writing it,

00:37:38.120 --> 00:37:39.240
I was writing it on spec.

00:37:39.240 --> 00:37:40.930
I had no idea it
would be published.

00:37:40.930 --> 00:37:44.000
I wasn't really thinking
about the future.

00:37:44.000 --> 00:37:51.630
And then when it became a
trilogy, it was incredibly fun.

00:37:51.630 --> 00:37:55.120
I really got to
explore this world.

00:37:55.120 --> 00:37:57.660
But when I got to
the third book,

00:37:57.660 --> 00:38:01.097
I realized I needed to end it.

00:38:01.097 --> 00:38:02.805
For me as a writer,
there's a funny thing

00:38:02.805 --> 00:38:04.805
that happens when you're
writing a series, which

00:38:04.805 --> 00:38:08.000
is that you're playing this
delicate game in which you're

00:38:08.000 --> 00:38:11.010
wrapping up, sort of the
local narrative threads.

00:38:11.010 --> 00:38:13.340
And the broader
narrative threads

00:38:13.340 --> 00:38:16.730
have to dangle
and keep on going.

00:38:16.730 --> 00:38:18.580
You have to sort
of something back.

00:38:18.580 --> 00:38:20.420
When I came to the
third book, I realized

00:38:20.420 --> 00:38:21.640
that I needed a free hand.

00:38:21.640 --> 00:38:23.120
I needed to be able
to kill whoever

00:38:23.120 --> 00:38:27.140
I wanted to kill, marry off
whoever I wanted to marry,

00:38:27.140 --> 00:38:29.850
raze the cities, salt the Earth.

00:38:29.850 --> 00:38:31.580
I felt like I had
to stop holding back

00:38:31.580 --> 00:38:33.430
and just be able
to just do whatever

00:38:33.430 --> 00:38:36.690
I like without an
eye on the next book.

00:38:36.690 --> 00:38:40.290
Also I had run out of ideas.

00:38:40.290 --> 00:38:44.480
So, you know, so I'm
super pro-long series.

00:38:44.480 --> 00:38:47.070
And my hat is off to the
people who can sustain them,

00:38:47.070 --> 00:38:49.920
like Martin.

00:38:49.920 --> 00:38:53.620
But you know when
your business is

00:38:53.620 --> 00:38:55.989
finished in a particular
universe, at least

00:38:55.989 --> 00:38:56.780
for the time being.

00:38:56.780 --> 00:39:00.580
I'm always mindful that Le Guin
went back to Earthsea, what,

00:39:00.580 --> 00:39:02.430
20 years later?

00:39:02.430 --> 00:39:07.040
Many years later, and realized
that she had something more

00:39:07.040 --> 00:39:08.540
to say there.

00:39:08.540 --> 00:39:13.460
And you know, I would never
rule that out about this world.

00:39:13.460 --> 00:39:16.360
But I couldn't do the
balancing act any longer.

00:39:16.360 --> 00:39:19.340
I've given it up for now.

00:39:19.340 --> 00:39:21.690
AUDIENCE: Hi, thank
