00:39:21.690 --> 00:39:23.940
One way to think
about literary fiction

00:39:23.940 --> 00:39:27.010
is that a set of techniques like
realism and a sort of concerns

00:39:27.010 --> 00:39:29.422
that you can apply to
other things like fantasy.

00:39:29.422 --> 00:39:30.880
Another way to
think about it might

00:39:30.880 --> 00:39:34.680
be as its own genre with its
own tropes and things like that.

00:39:37.270 --> 00:39:38.577
I like, "The Magicians" a lot.

00:39:38.577 --> 00:39:40.160
If I had to criticize
it a little bit,

00:39:40.160 --> 00:39:43.612
I might say it was much more
playful with the fantasy tropes

00:39:43.612 --> 00:39:45.820
then it was about any of
the literary fiction tropes.

00:39:48.810 --> 00:39:50.750
I wonder if you think
of literary fiction

00:39:50.750 --> 00:39:54.310
as a genre like
that, or not, or why?

00:39:54.310 --> 00:39:56.720
LEV GROSSMAN: It's a
really important question.

00:39:56.720 --> 00:40:00.347
And I do think of it that way.

00:40:00.347 --> 00:40:02.680
Another quote which I will
mangle and fail to attribute,

00:40:02.680 --> 00:40:05.344
because I can't remember
who said it-- somebody once

00:40:05.344 --> 00:40:07.010
said about literary
fiction, "the sooner

00:40:07.010 --> 00:40:10.120
that literary fiction
can wake up and recognize

00:40:10.120 --> 00:40:13.890
it's status as a genre, the
sooner it can get the help

00:40:13.890 --> 00:40:16.490
it so desperately needs."

00:40:16.490 --> 00:40:19.180
There is a sense, you
know, that literary fiction

00:40:19.180 --> 00:40:22.610
that holds itself apart that
has a sort of exceptionalism

00:40:22.610 --> 00:40:23.936
about it.

00:40:23.936 --> 00:40:26.330
But it is another genre.

00:40:26.330 --> 00:40:31.000
And yeah, it's true.

00:40:31.000 --> 00:40:34.570
I mean, I thought a lot
about "The Magicians" books

00:40:34.570 --> 00:40:43.590
as a collision between
literary fiction and fantasy.

00:40:43.590 --> 00:40:47.152
And I guess in that collision,
if one of the bodies

00:40:47.152 --> 00:40:49.110
crumpled more than the
other, it was definitely

00:40:49.110 --> 00:40:50.080
fantasy that crumpled.

00:40:52.810 --> 00:40:56.270
And, you know, I'm aware that.

00:40:56.270 --> 00:40:58.920
The model for them was
very much Watchmen.

00:40:58.920 --> 00:41:03.570
Watchman was-- I'm super old so
I read Watchmen in high school

00:41:03.570 --> 00:41:05.090
when it first came out.

00:41:05.090 --> 00:41:07.590
And it was totally
transformative for me.

00:41:07.590 --> 00:41:09.834
And I often thought, when
I was trying to figure out

00:41:09.834 --> 00:41:12.125
what the model was for the
magicians, it was, you know,

00:41:12.125 --> 00:41:15.590
to try to interrogate the
fantasy genre in the same way

00:41:15.590 --> 00:41:19.390
that Moore and Gibbons
interrogated the superhero

00:41:19.390 --> 00:41:22.010
story.

00:41:22.010 --> 00:41:25.050
Now to write the Watchmen
of literary fiction-- well,

00:41:25.050 --> 00:41:29.010
I mean, in some ways I felt
that work had been done

00:41:29.010 --> 00:41:32.160
by people like Joyce and Woolf.

00:41:35.910 --> 00:41:43.050
They took the
Victorian novel, they

00:41:43.050 --> 00:41:46.010
sort of looked at the kind
of bland epistemological

00:41:46.010 --> 00:41:48.240
certainties of out of it
and just disassembled.

00:41:48.240 --> 00:41:51.700
Took it to pieces and
just left it lying

00:41:51.700 --> 00:41:56.160
and its component parts
on the garage floor.

00:41:56.160 --> 00:41:57.835
And said, just
look at this mess.

00:41:57.835 --> 00:41:59.680
You know, this
ridiculous machine.

00:41:59.680 --> 00:42:01.530
We just took it apart for you.

00:42:01.530 --> 00:42:03.990
And in a lot of ways,
I felt as though I

00:42:03.990 --> 00:42:08.090
was doing something
radical to literary fiction

00:42:08.090 --> 00:42:11.910
just by walking that back.

00:42:11.910 --> 00:42:17.890
By writing a book that was about
the pleasure of storytelling,

00:42:17.890 --> 00:42:21.990
that stopped saying, look how
false and wrong, you know,

00:42:21.990 --> 00:42:24.410
these narratives are.

00:42:24.410 --> 00:42:26.490
Let's stare at the
ways in which they

00:42:26.490 --> 00:42:30.050
failed to represent reality,
and was a little bit more like,

00:42:30.050 --> 00:42:33.050
actually let's go back and
see what they have to teach us

00:42:33.050 --> 00:42:35.390
and why they're so pleasurable.

00:42:35.390 --> 00:42:37.840
But, yeah, I don't know.

00:42:37.840 --> 00:42:40.070
I didn't know how
to get traction

00:42:40.070 --> 00:42:41.640
on literary fiction
in the same way

00:42:41.640 --> 00:42:45.860
that I felt like I had
something to say about fantasy.

00:42:45.860 --> 00:42:48.920
But I'd love to read the book
that did it the other way.

00:42:52.970 --> 00:42:53.700
AUDIENCE: Hi.

00:42:53.700 --> 00:42:55.990
So I've read the first
two chapters of the book

00:42:55.990 --> 00:42:57.864
and I'm looking forward
to reading more of it

00:42:57.864 --> 00:42:58.590
after this talk.

00:42:58.590 --> 00:43:00.760
So thank you for that.

00:43:00.760 --> 00:43:03.530
My question is about, kind of,
not about the series, not about

00:43:03.530 --> 00:43:07.890
fantasy, but as you as a
writer, and as a critic.

00:43:07.890 --> 00:43:10.140
You could argue that, kind
of the rise of social media

00:43:10.140 --> 00:43:14.869
has brought public figures
closer to the public.

00:43:14.869 --> 00:43:15.660
LEV GROSSMAN: Yeah.

00:43:15.660 --> 00:43:19.912
AUDIENCE: And I'm on a
website called Goodreads.

00:43:19.912 --> 00:43:21.120
LEV GROSSMAN: I know it well.

00:43:21.120 --> 00:43:24.950
AUDIENCE: And you've been
very prevalent or very active

00:43:24.950 --> 00:43:27.530
on your own Goodreads account.

00:43:27.530 --> 00:43:29.924
Goodreads, for those
who don't know,

00:43:29.924 --> 00:43:32.340
is where you can keep track,
catalog the books that you've

00:43:32.340 --> 00:43:36.990
read, write reviews, socialize,
join groups, join reading

00:43:36.990 --> 00:43:39.452
challenges, things like that.

00:43:39.452 --> 00:43:40.660
So you have your own account.

00:43:40.660 --> 00:43:45.050
You have books that you've read
and have a link to your blog.

00:43:45.050 --> 00:43:48.490
And so you've been very active,
engaging with your audience.

00:43:48.490 --> 00:43:50.700
Recently you've
also annotated one

00:43:50.700 --> 00:43:53.840
of the chapters of your
book on genius.com,

00:43:53.840 --> 00:43:58.410
rapgenius.com, which I
thought was pretty cool.

00:43:58.410 --> 00:44:03.760
So my question is, as a
critic working for Time,

00:44:03.760 --> 00:44:08.220
do you see this sort of melding
of public and public figure

00:44:08.220 --> 00:44:12.390
opinions about media
that people produce,

00:44:12.390 --> 00:44:16.160
as kind of being the
way forward for just

00:44:16.160 --> 00:44:21.200
kind of a discussion on media
that's out in the public?

00:44:21.200 --> 00:44:24.262
And you can give the
opinions of others

00:44:24.262 --> 00:44:25.720
that you've heard,
your own opinion

00:44:25.720 --> 00:44:28.610
or if time has it
in the contract

00:44:28.610 --> 00:44:30.640
that you can't say
too much about this,

00:44:30.640 --> 00:44:33.510
then give that as well.

00:44:33.510 --> 00:44:35.974
What are your thoughts?

00:44:35.974 --> 00:44:37.640
LEV GROSSMAN: It's
an interesting issue,

00:44:37.640 --> 00:44:40.090
which I think this is
really under-discussed.

00:44:40.090 --> 00:44:44.051
I mean, the climate in which
books are read and written,

00:44:44.051 --> 00:44:45.800
just the sort of
informational environment

00:44:45.800 --> 00:44:47.640
in which this happens
has completely

00:44:47.640 --> 00:44:53.860
transformed in the past
10 years, 15 years,

00:44:53.860 --> 00:44:55.470
and in a very strange way.

00:44:55.470 --> 00:44:57.360
I mean, barriers and
boundaries that we

00:44:57.360 --> 00:45:04.840
think of as firm and solid
are completely porous.

00:45:04.840 --> 00:45:06.720
It's actually an
anecdote worth telling

00:45:06.720 --> 00:45:10.390
that my mom met CS Lewis and
had a little chat with him.

00:45:10.390 --> 00:45:12.830
Now, when people finish, "The
Magicians," the first thing

00:45:12.830 --> 00:45:13.950
they do is Google me.

00:45:13.950 --> 00:45:16.030
They see that I'm on
Twitter and tweet at me

00:45:16.030 --> 00:45:18.180
and we have a little exchange.

00:45:18.180 --> 00:45:20.450
So the quantity of
information that's

00:45:20.450 --> 00:45:24.680
flying back and forth between
reader and writer is enormous.

00:45:24.680 --> 00:45:28.200
And in effects the way
that books are written

00:45:28.200 --> 00:45:33.154
and I think experienced in ways
that are hard to understand.

00:45:33.154 --> 00:45:34.820
I mean, in some ways
I think it's great.

00:45:34.820 --> 00:45:39.140
One of the reasons I'm
on Twitter and Goodreads

00:45:39.140 --> 00:45:46.030
is just because I don't really
like this sense that it's

00:45:46.030 --> 00:45:48.110
easy to get, that
authors are austere

00:45:48.110 --> 00:45:55.214
or sort of mystical
beings, even godlike.

00:45:55.214 --> 00:45:58.740
You know, they're
just normal people

00:45:58.740 --> 00:46:01.470
who are trying to words
together like anybody else.

00:46:01.470 --> 00:46:03.220
And I like that sort
of de-mystification

00:46:03.220 --> 00:46:06.590
that is accomplished
by social media.

00:46:06.590 --> 00:46:07.640
But it's a strange thing.

00:46:07.640 --> 00:46:08.910
And as a writer,
you definitely have

00:46:08.910 --> 00:46:10.451
to watch it because,
you know, you're

00:46:10.451 --> 00:46:15.860
really getting a ton of
feedback in near real-time

00:46:15.860 --> 00:46:18.380
as to how people are
reacting to your work.

00:46:18.380 --> 00:46:20.052
And, you know,
there's a temptation

00:46:20.052 --> 00:46:21.760
to kind of bob and
weave and sort of feed

00:46:21.760 --> 00:46:23.176
that back into
what you're writing

00:46:23.176 --> 00:46:25.154
and think, oh, you know
that guy tweeted me.

00:46:25.154 --> 00:46:26.570
He's going to love
this, you know.

00:46:26.570 --> 00:46:29.390
And I better not do that
because this other person

00:46:29.390 --> 00:46:31.660
didn't like it.

00:46:31.660 --> 00:46:34.800
You know, you'll rapidly
go insane and also write

00:46:34.800 --> 00:46:36.720
really bad novels,
if you're just

00:46:36.720 --> 00:46:40.010
trying to guess what
people want all the time.

00:46:40.010 --> 00:46:41.970
It's a strange thing,
and I am absolutely

00:46:41.970 --> 00:46:47.780
sure that it's changing
literature in significant ways.

00:46:47.780 --> 00:46:49.340
I don't quite know
how yet, but I

00:46:49.340 --> 00:46:51.450
think later we're going
to go back and notice

00:46:51.450 --> 00:46:57.390
that this was an inflection
point and very weird one.

00:46:57.390 --> 00:47:00.550
AUDIENCE: So this is probably
a slightly rude question.

00:47:00.550 --> 00:47:02.740
But sparked from a
couple of answers

00:47:02.740 --> 00:47:06.010
ago, what thoughts are
you willing to share about

00:47:06.010 --> 00:47:06.820
where next?

00:47:06.820 --> 00:47:11.700
As you say, you've sort of
salted the earth and moved on.

00:47:11.700 --> 00:47:14.634
What are you willing to
say about what's next?

00:47:14.634 --> 00:47:16.050
LEV GROSSMAN: Well,
what I'm doing

00:47:16.050 --> 00:47:19.614
next-- I'll tell
you what I'm not

00:47:19.614 --> 00:47:22.030
doing next, which is this book
that I just spent a year on

00:47:22.030 --> 00:47:25.510
and then didn't work out.

00:47:25.510 --> 00:47:28.640
I'm still sulking
from that experience.

00:47:28.640 --> 00:47:30.490
It's a strange thing.

00:47:30.490 --> 00:47:33.510
I've actually
written five novels,

00:47:33.510 --> 00:47:37.740
and yet it's still possible
for me to get completely lost,

00:47:37.740 --> 00:47:41.760
go down a rabbit hole, throw
away tens and tens of thousands

00:47:41.760 --> 00:47:46.140
of words on something
that's just not working out.

00:47:46.140 --> 00:47:49.050
I now feel like I've found
the trail again with something

00:47:49.050 --> 00:47:51.145
else.

00:47:51.145 --> 00:47:51.855
It is fantasy.

00:47:54.720 --> 00:47:57.720
I think it's going to
feel very different from,

00:47:57.720 --> 00:47:58.450
"The Magicians."

00:47:58.450 --> 00:48:01.405
I've been reading a
lot of Thomas Malory.

00:48:04.570 --> 00:48:06.860
He's one of the many
hundreds of people

00:48:06.860 --> 00:48:12.076
who wrote a version
of the Arthurian epic.

00:48:12.076 --> 00:48:13.367
I've been reading a lot of him.

00:48:16.320 --> 00:48:18.390
That's probably
all I should say.

00:48:18.390 --> 00:48:22.890
But that's where my
research is going right now.

00:48:22.890 --> 00:48:25.660
I think that's probably
it for the hour.

00:48:25.660 --> 00:48:27.030
Thank you all for coming.

00:48:27.030 --> 00:48:28.880
And for those who
didn't come anyway, just

00:48:28.880 --> 00:48:30.670
are watching at your
desks, thank you too.

00:48:30.670 --> 00:48:31.170
Thank you.

